9:
Oh, Stella. Lovely timing as always.
Would you mind standing over there 
a moment?
17:
Perfect... What a stunning angle. Now, 
hold still.
26:
...A few more strokes... and there! Quite 
a good likeness, if I do say so myself.
33:
I'm done now, Stella. There's no need 
to pull such a silly face.
36:
It was unintentional.
...What are you painting, Melsele?
39: It's me and you. Alone, in this town.
42:
Yes... It looks quite forlorn, doesn't it? 
But not to worry. I haven't finished yet.
46:
There's Alk... and Light... and the rest of 
our companions. It's beautiful.
50:
Yes. I must say, I am very pleased with 
it.
52:
...See, paintings are like a light, which 
reilluminate your memories.
54: It's how we elves remember things.
62: Journals... Yes, you could say they are.
65:
Do the other elves put as much time 
into their paintings?
68:
Oh, yes. In fact, most would say my 
painting was rather rushed.
75:
It's normal to take a few decades, at 
least. Why, some elves will take 
upwards of 200 years.
78: What do they draw for 200 years?
82:
Our forest. The whispering trees, 
shining silver in the moonlight... Even 
on canvas, they continue to glow.
86:
But they're so beautiful, so 
unchanging, they feel almost cold at 
times... I myself was always drawn to 
the rainbow colors of the outside 
world.
90:
I understand... Your painting feels 
alive.
95:
Thank you, Stella. We really are birds of 
a feather.
100: ...Why have you left this space blank?
105:
Oh, the spot next to me? Well, I'm 
saving it. For someone very special.
112:
Why, yes. She's my very best friend. 
The brightest light we had in the forest
we called her Starflame.
116:
Naturally, she has quite a way of 
standing out. I'm certain that, no 
matter how the world changes, she is 
the one person I'll always find my way 
back to.
